hands_on_practices.problem:
A linear time-invariant (LTI) system is a fundamental concept in signal processing and control theory. The behavior of such a system is fully characterized by its response to a standard input signal. Consider a particular LTI system that is initially at rest. When subjected to a unit step input, $u(t)$, where $u(t) = 1$ for $t \ge 0$ and $u(t) = 0$ for $t < 0$, the system's output is found to be $y_{step}(t) = 5(1 - \exp(-0.5t))u(t)$.

A new input signal, $x(t)$, is now applied to this system, which is again initially at rest. This signal is a rectangular pulse of amplitude 3 that starts at $t=1$ second and ends at $t=4$ seconds. More formally, the input is defined as:
$$
x(t) = 
\begin{cases} 
3 & 1 \le t < 4 \\
0 & \text{otherwise} 
\end{cases}
$$
Determine the numerical value of the system's output, $y(t)$, at the time $t = 5$ seconds. Provide your answer rounded to three significant figures.
